      <profileDesc>
         <abstract>
            <p>Contrary to the regular use of the term <foreign xml:lang="ar">ʿilm al-farāʾid</foreign> (lit. "the science of the obligations of law") 
               in Muslim law, this work does not primarily concern hereditary law. Instead the treatise is made up of two parts with different content. 
               The first by the author <persName ref="PRS1179Abdarra" role="author"/> contains sayings based on numbers, such as: ‘Four things
               do not last forever: the friendship of a liar, the wedding dinner of a miser, the wealth of this world and the shadow of a cloud’. Some of 
               these include religious contents and obligations. The second part by <persName ref="PRS9354Tayyiba" role="author"/> starts with 
               a catechism-like commentary on a creed. The articles of faith are first given in Arabic and then explained in Harari. Later religious
               formulae are also interpreted and religious duties enumerated.</p>
         </abstract>
